Recap: A Typical Data Science Project

A typical data science project looks like this

In this session, we will show you how to leverage R in every step by completing 3 beginner contests in Kaggle

First things first, what is Kaggle anyway

Kaggle is an online community of data scientists and machine learners.

Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaggle

You can sign up your kaggle account easily

https://www.kaggle.com/account/login

What to do after signing up?

  • Learn
  • Competitions
  • Discussion

How to learn Kaggle

https://www.kaggle.com/learn/overview

Kaggle Competitions are its core assets

There are 7 categories in Kaggle Competitions

  • Featured
  • Research
  • Recruitment
  • Getting started
  • Masters
  • Playground
  • Analytics

3 competitions to get started

  • House Prices: Advanced Regression Techniques
  • Titanic: Machine Learning from Disaster
  • Digit Recognizer

Okay, get the prerequisites done in R

Packages to install

packages_to_install <- c("dplyr", "ggplot2", "caret", "rpart", "randomForest")
install.packages(packages_to_install)

Packages to library

library("dplyr")
library("ggplot2")
library("caret")
library("rpart")
library("randomForest")

Import

Titanic: Machine Learning from Disaster

train <- read.csv("https://s3-ap-northeast-1.amazonaws.com/kaggle-getting-started/titanic/train.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
test <- read.csv("https://s3-ap-northeast-1.amazonaws.com/kaggle-getting-started/titanic/test.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
titanic <- list(
  train =  train,
  test = test
)

House Prices: Advanced Regression Techniques

train <- read.csv("https://s3-ap-northeast-1.amazonaws.com/kaggle-getting-started/house-prices/train.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
test <- read.csv("https://s3-ap-northeast-1.amazonaws.com/kaggle-getting-started/house-prices/test.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
housing <- list(
  train =  train,
  test = test
)

Digit Recognizer

train <- read.csv("https://s3-ap-northeast-1.amazonaws.com/kaggle-getting-started/mnist/train.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
test <- read.csv("https://s3-ap-northeast-1.amazonaws.com/kaggle-getting-started/mnist/test.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
mnist <- list(
  train = train,
  test = test
)

Tidy and Transform

Titanic and House Prices are both suitable for practicing the skills of feature engineering

  • Log transformation
  • Standardization
  • One-hot encoding
  • Matrix manipulation
  • …etc.

House SalePrice BEFORE log transformation

ggplot(housing$train, aes(x = SalePrice)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins=100)

House SalePrice AFTER log transformation

ggplot(housing$train, aes(x = SalePrice)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins=100) +
  scale_x_log10()

We can have a more LINEAR relationship via log transformation

ggplot(housing$train, aes(x = GrLivArea, y = SalePrice)) + 
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10()

Titanic passenger Fare BEFORE standardization

ggplot(titanic$train, aes(x = Fare)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 100)

Titanic passenger Fare AFTER standardization

mean_fare <- mean(titanic$train$Fare)
std_fare <- sd(titanic$train$Fare)
titanic$train$FareStandardized <- (titanic$train$Fare - mean_fare)/std_fare
ggplot(titanic$train, aes(x = FareStandardized)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 100)

dummy <- dummyVars(" ~ Embarked", data = titanic$train, fullRank = TRUE)
ohe_Embarked <- data.frame(predict(dummy, newdata = titanic$train))

Visualise

Exploring data insights via different types of plot

  • Using scatter for correlations
  • Using histogram for distributions
  • Using bar for rankings
  • Using image for pixel matrice
  • …etc.

Exploring correlations between House SalePrice and GrLivArea

ggplot(housing$train, aes(x = GrLivArea, y = SalePrice)) + 
  geom_point()

Exploring distribution with House SalePrice

ggplot(housing$train, aes(x = SalePrice)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins=100)

Exploring rankings with Titanic Embarked

ggplot(titanic$train, aes(x = Embarked, fill=Embarked)) + 
  geom_bar()

Visualising a pixel matrix

image(first_image_matrix, axes=FALSE, useRaster = TRUE, col=gray((0:255)/255))

Exploring more on “Visualize”

  • ggplot2

Model

Predicting SalePrice for Housing test

# data manipulation
test_labels <- housing$test$Id
housing$test$Id <- NULL
housing$train$Id <- NULL
housing$test$SalePrice <- NA
train_test <- rbind(housing$train, housing$test)
numericVars <- which(sapply(train_test, is.numeric))
factorVars <- which(sapply(train_test, is.factor))
all_numVar <- train_test[, numericVars]
cor_numVar <- cor(all_numVar, use = "pairwise.complete.obs")
cor_sorted <- as.matrix(sort(cor_numVar[, 'SalePrice'], decreasing = TRUE))
CorHigh <- names(which(apply(cor_sorted, 1, function(x) abs(x)>0.5)))
cor_numVar <- cor_numVar[CorHigh, CorHigh]
cor_high_vars <- names(cor_numVar[, 1])
combined <- train_test[, cor_high_vars]
# modeling
train1 <- combined[!is.na(train_test$SalePrice), ]
test1 <- combined[is.na(train_test$SalePrice), ]
test1 <- test1[, -1]
lm_fit <- lm(formula = SalePrice ~ ., data = train1)
# predicting
y_pred <- predict(lm_fit, test1)
y_pred[1:10]

Preparing submission for Housing

submission <- data.frame(

Predicting Survived for Titanic test

# data manipulation
titanic$test$Survived <- NA
train_test <- bind_rows(titanic$train, titanic$test)
train_test$Embarked[c(62, 830)] <- 'C'
train_test$Fare[1044] <- median(train_test[train_test$Pclass == '3' & train_test$Embarked == 'S', ]$Fare, na.rm = TRUE)
age_missing <- is.na(train_test$Age)
train_test$Age[age_missing] <- median(train_test$Age, na.rm = TRUE)
# modeling
train1 <- train_test[1:891, ]
test1 <- train_test[892:nrow(train_test), ]
dt_model <- rpart(formula = factor(Survived) ~ Pclass + Sex + Age + SibSp + Parch + Fare + Embarked, data = train1)

# predicting
y_pred <- predict(dt_model, test1[, c('Pclass', 'Sex', 'Age', 'SibSp', 'Parch', 'Fare', 'Embarked')], type = "class")

Preparing submission for Titanic

submission <- data.frame(
  PassengerId = as.integer(row.names(test1)),
  Survived = y_pred
)
write.csv(submission, row.names = FALSE, file = 'titanic_submission.csv')

Predicting label for MNIST test

# data manipulation
numTrain <- 10000
numTrees <- 25
rows <- sample(1:nrow(mnist$train), numTrain)
labels <- as.factor(mnist$train[rows,1])
train <- mnist$train[rows, -1]
# modeling
rf <- randomForest(train, labels, xtest = mnist$test, ntree = numTrees)
# predicting
y_pred <- rf$test$predicted

Preparing submission for MNIST

submission <- data.frame(
  PassengerId = as.integer(row.names(mnist$test)),
  Survived = y_pred
)
write.csv(submission, row.names = FALSE, file = 'mnist_submission.csv')

Tips for a self-taught machine learning engineer

Recap: the Venn-diagram of data science

A quote from Shane Legg’s tweet

Learn: 1. linear algebra well (e.g. matrix math) 2. calculus to an ok level (not advanced stuff) 3. prob. theory and stats to a good level 4. theoretical computer science basics 5. to code well in Python and ok in C++

Then read and implement ML papers and play with stuff! :-)
